ribed to allow the study to be repeated?: **Yes**\n* Is the use of statistics and treatment of uncertainties appropriate?: **Yes**\n* Is the presentation of the work clear?: **No**\n* Are the images in this manuscript (including electrophoretic gels and blots) free from apparent manipulation?: **No**\n"},{"type":"reviewerAgreed","content":"","date":"2020-11-03T01:00:00+00:00","index":3,"fulltext":""},{"type":"reviewerAgreed","content":"","date":"2020-11-03T00:00:00+00:00","index":2,"fulltext":""},{"type":"reviewersInvited","content":"","date":"2020-11-01T00:00:00+00:00","index":"","fulltext":""},{"type":"reviewerAgreed","content":"","date":"2020-11-01T00:00:00+00:00","index":1,"fulltext":""},{"type":"editorAssigned","content":"","date":"2020-10-28T12:00:00+00:00","index":"","fulltext":""},{"type":"checksComplete","content":"","date":"2020-10-27T12:00:00+00:00","index":"","fulltext":""},{"type":"editorInvited","content":"","date":"2020-10-27T12:00:00+00:00","index":"","fulltext":""}],"status":"published","journal":{"display":true,"email":"info@researchsquare.com","identity":"bmc-medical-informatics-and-decision-making","isNatureJournal":false,"hasQc":true,"allowDirectSubmit":false,"externalIdentity":"midm","sideBox":"Learn more about [BMC Medical Informatics and Decision Making](http://bmcmedinformdecismak.biomedcentral.com/)","snPcode":"","submissionUrl":"https://www.editorialmanager.com/midm/default.aspx","title":"BMC Medical Informatics and Decision Making","twitterHandle":"BMC_series","acdcEnabled":true,"dfaEnabled":false,"editorialSystem":"em","reportingPortfolio":"BMC Series","inReviewEnabled":true,"inReviewRevisionsEnabled":true}},{"code":1,"date":"2020-08-11 17:21:53","doi":"10.21203/rs.3.rs-54715/v1","editorialEvents":[{"type":"communityComments","content":0},{"type":"decision","content":"Major revision","date":"2020-09-23T12:00:00+00:00","index":"","fulltext":""},{"type":"editorInvitedReview","content":"","date":"2020-09-16T12:00:00+00:00","index":1,"fulltext":"Recommendation: Accept after minor essential revisions\nForm responses:\n---\n\nComments to Author:\n---\nThe manuscript is well orgnization but need to enhancement of multi points:\n\n1. Rewrite the title from zero to become accept as title for manuscript, also, make the abstract focus of the problem, idea, algorithm to solve it and result not exceed half page.  \n\n2. Write complete algorithm represent the proposal method base on suitable format\n\n3. Add new section under title the hypothesis and limitations of the develop method present by author(s).\n\n4. Multi points in this manuscript need justification and prove by the author(S), [Hinte: justification meaning more discuss from the author to become more clearly, while prove the results as values such as z=x+y then y=z-x] this meaning in each step give me the opinion of you as author this is very important\n\n5. Update the references list by adding the following reference related to your'work and all these references indexing in  ISI and Scopus Database, please make at possible most reference related to the last five years and refre DOI for all reference  \n\n\n----  A nifty collaborative analysis to predicting a novel tool (DRFLLS) for missing values estimation, Springer, journal Soft Computing, 2020\nDoi: 10.1007/s00500-019-03972-x\n\n---Evaluation prediction techniques to achievement an optimal biomedical analysis', Int. J. Grid and Utility Computing, Vol. 10, No. 5, pp.512-527.\n\n-----A Novel Software to Improve Healthcare Base on Predictive Analytics and Mobile Services for Cloud Data Centers. In: Farhaoui Y. (eds) Big Data and Networks Technologies. BDNT 2019. Lecture Notes in Networks and Systems, vol 81. Springer, Cham, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-23672-4_23\n\n----An Innovative synthesis of deep learning techniques (DCapsNet \u0026 DCOM) for generation electrical renewable energy from wind energy. Soft Comput 24, 10943-10962 (2020). https://doi.org/10.1007/s00500-020-04905-9\n\n---Miner for OACCR: Case of medical data analysis in knowledge discovery,\" IEEE, 2012 6th International Conference on Sciences of Electronics, Technologies of Information and Telecommunications (SETIT), Sousse, 2012, pp. 962-975.\nDoi: 10.1109/SETIT.2012.6482043\nURL: http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/stamp/stamp.jsp?tp=\u0026arnumber=6482043\u0026isnumber=6481878\n\n\n------Empirical rapid and accurate prediction model for data mining tasks in cloud computing environments,\" IEEE, 2014 International Congress on Technology, Communication and Knowledge (ICTCK), Mashhad, 2014, pp. 1-8.\ndoi: 10.1109/ICTCK.2014.7033495\n\n\n6. Add section under title discuss explain on it the advantages/disadvantage of this manscription i based on the researcher(s)'opinion to become as Guide of the other future researchers work at the same field , at the same time to increase the weight of your manuscript.\n\n7.  Preparing table show the compare among the previous works and put that table at the end of section \" Related work\" in addition, must add (two - three lines) after each previous work show in that lines you as authors similar and different with that previous works at any point.\n\n8. redraw figures from zero because color of all figures and resolution(quality) not accept.* Publons Reviewer Recognition. Springer Nature can send verification of this review directly to Publons (a subsidiary of Clarivate Analytics). If you would like to take advantage of this service, please click on the “Yes” option below. Your name, email address, title of the reviewed manuscript, name of the journal, and date of your review submission (the “Review Data”) will then be transmitted to Publons upon publication of the manuscript. If you have already registered at Publons, they will notify you of the receipt of this review and update your profile as per your settings and their policy. If you are not registered with Publons, you will receive an email from them asking you to register in order for them to be able to recognize your review on your new profile page. Publons may use the Review Data to generate derivative metadata for the benefit of Publons and you as a reviewer, carefully considering the sensitivity of such information. For example, Publons may verify your record as a reviewer by updating your profile published on its webservice if you have registered for such service or help editors to identify candidate reviewers. Please find the details of processing in Publons’ privacy policy https://publons.com/about/terms: **Yes**\n* Declaration of competing interests: **I declare...**\n* Reviewer Publication Consent. I agree for my report to be made available under an Open Access Creative Commons CC-BY License (http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0) if this manuscript is accepted for publication. Any comments that I do not wish to be included in the published report have been included as confidential comments to the editor, which will not be published.: **I agree to the terms of the CC-BY 4.0 license; please do not publish my name with my report. (default)**\n* Is the study design appropriate to answer the research question (including the use of appropriate controls), and are the conclusions supported by the evidence presented?: **Yes**\n* Are the methods sufficiently described to allow the study to be repeated?: **Yes**\n* Is the use of statistics and treatment of uncertainties appropriate?: **Yes**\n* Is the presentation of the work clear?: **No**\n* Are the images in this manuscript (including electrophoretic gels and blots) free from apparent manipulation?: **No**\n"},{"type":"editorInvitedReview","content":"","date":"2020-09-16T12:00:00+00:00","index":2,"fulltext":"Recommendation: Reject\nForm responses:\n---\n\nComments to Author:\n---\nIn this paper the authors presented an empirical study of four strategies to deal with the problem of loss to followup in the context of predicting an event within a certain period of time. While this is an important problem to address, there is little new insight we may gain from this paper.  Below are several concerns with this paper:\n1. It would be helpful if a clear and rigorous definition of \"outcome\" and \"loss to follow up\" could be given.\n2. A more detailed explanation of the four strategies is recommenced. This is more important given the lack of a rigorous definition of \"outcome\" and \"loss to followup\", Consider the second strategy, which would include all patients, including those loss to followup before reporting outcome. It is not clear how the data with missing outcome are used by the classification model. Is this by imputation? Or by some semi-supervised learning method? Or as the choice i) at the beginning of page 5, where the the patients lost to followup are labelled as the latest information available for them?\n3. While extensive simulation study was performed and conclusions were drawn, there is no theoretic support for these conclusions. Therefore, the paper fails to convince the readers that the simulation results are not something peculiar to the specific data set, specific outcome variable, specific statistical model, specific variables included in the model, or specific way the simulation data were generated.* Publons Reviewer Recognition. Springer Nature can send verification of this review directly to Publons (a subsidiary of Clarivate Analytics). If you would like to take advantage of this service, please click on the “Yes” option below. Your name, email address, title of the reviewed manuscript, name of the journal, and date of your review submission (the “Review Data”) will then be transmitted to Publons upon publication of the manuscript. If you have already registered at Publons, they will notify you of the receipt of this review and update your profile as per your settings and their policy. If you are not registered with Publons, you will receive an email from them asking you to register in order for them to be able to recognize your review on your new profile page. Publons may use the Review Data to generate derivative metadata for the benefit of Publons and you as a reviewer, carefully considering the sensitivity of such information. For example, Publons may verify your record as a reviewer by updating your profile published on its webservice if you have registered for such service or help editors to identify candidate reviewers. Please find the details of processing in Publons’ privacy policy https://publons.com/about/terms: **No**\n* Declaration of competing interests: **I declare that I have no competing interests.**\n* Reviewer Publication Consent. I agree for my report to be made available under an Open Access Creative Commons CC-BY License (http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0) if this manuscript is accepted for publication. Any comments that I do not wish to be included in the published report have been included as confidential comments to the editor, which will not be published.: **I agree to the terms of the CC-BY 4.0 license; please do not publish my name with my report. (default)**\n* Is the study design appropriate to answer the research question (including the use of appropriate controls), and are the conclusions supported by the evidence presented?: **No**\n* Are the methods sufficiently described to allow the study to be repeated?: **No**\n* Is the use of statistics and treatment of uncertainties appropriate?: **Yes**\n* Is the presentation of the work clear?: **No**\n* Are the images in this manuscript (including electrophoretic gels and blots) free from apparent manipulation?: **Yes**\n"},{"type":"editorInvitedReview","content":"","date":"2020-09-07T12:00:00+00:00","index":3,"fulltext":"Recommendation: Accept after discretionary revisions\nForm responses:\n---\n\nComments to Author:\n---\n\nDear Authors,\nI have found your work on addressing the inclusion or exclusion of lost to follow-up patients in developing prediction models particularly interesting and well-composed.\n\nIn my opinion, the manuscript, as in its present state, is almost ready for publication. I would only want to add some minor comments that might help to improve an already excellent article; so I am recommending its acceptance after discretionary revisions.\n\nAs a general comment, although I usually enjoy some literary reference to the title of a research paper when suitable, I would advise on the contrary. However \"catchy\" it may be, the title \"An empirical analysis of dealing with patients who are lost to follow-up when developing prognostic models using a cohort design\" is both descriptive and sensitive to the content of the study.\n\nAdditionally, although I understand it as optional on the part of the authors, I would have favoured authors to include some comment on how the results of their investigation relate with the causal model generating the lost to follow-up patients. It is currently implicit in the explanation of the deviations of the model whenever authors opted on excluding patients without the desired outcome prior to the lost to follow-up date, or when acknowledging the random generation of lost to-follow up patients in the synthetic data or the potential association of certain conditions with an increased probability of lost to follow-up but I think authors should take the opportunity to explicitly address lost to follow-up as a missing management issue and therefore link with the existing literature on this topic.  \n\nFinally, I would recommend the authors to check the manuscript for typos and correct the legend of the figures in Appendix A.\n\nKind regards,\n* Publons Reviewer Recognition. Springer Nature can send verification of this review directly to Publons (a subsidiary of Clarivate Analytics). If you would like to take advantage of this service, please click on the “Yes” option below. Your name, email address, title of the reviewed manuscript, name of the journal, and date of your review submission (the “Review Data”) will then be transmitted to Publons upon publication of the manuscript. If you have already registered at Publons, they will notify you of the receipt of this review and update your profile as per your settings and their policy. If you are not registered with Publons, you will receive an email from them asking you to register in order for them to be able to recognize your review on your new profile page. Publons may use the Review Data to generate derivative metadata for the benefit of Publons and you as a reviewer, carefully considering the sensitivity of such information. For example, Publons may verify your record as a reviewer by updating your profile published on its webservice if you have registered for such service or help editors to identify candidate reviewers. Please find the details of processing in Publons’ privacy policy https://publons.com/about/terms: **Yes**\n* Declaration of competing interests: **I declare that I have no competing interests**\n* Reviewer Publication Consent. I agree for my report to be made available under an Open Access Creative Commons CC-BY License (http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0) if this manuscript is accepted for publication. Any comments that I do not wish to be included in the published report have been included as confidential comments to the editor, which will not be published.: **I agree to the terms of the CC-BY 4.0 license; please do not publish my name with my report. (default)**\n* Is the study design appropriate to answer the research question (including the use of appropriate controls), and are the conclusions supported by the evidence presented?: **Yes**\n* Are the methods sufficiently described to allow the study to be repeated?: **Yes**\n* Is the use of statistics and treatment of uncertainties appropriate?: **Yes**\n* Is the presentation of the work clear?: **Yes**\n* Are the images in this manuscript (including electrophoretic gels and blots) free from apparent manipulation?: **Yes**\n"},{"type":"editorInvitedReview","conte